<br>
That’s the problem with moral relativism.  Who is the ultimate judge of what is right and what is wrong?  Society?  Ok… which society?  You local community?  Your state?  Your country?  And how, exactly, do you propose to establish such judgment?  Do you honestly believe that everyone can agree on what is right and what is wrong?  Hell no!  Someone will always disagree!  And who’s to judge if the one in disagreement is having his or her rights infringed upon?  So, where does that leave us?  Do we determine right and wrong by popular opinion?  Well, guess what?  That’s what we already have!  The majority world view in this country is based on Judeo-Christian dogma.  And that’s where the country gets its morality.  Get over it!<br>
<br>
The problem with moral relativism is that its logic is circular.<br>
